The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Ballarpur Industries Ltd (Bilt) has posted a net profit of Rs 66.28 crore for the quarter ended June 30 compared with Rs 67.88 crore in the corresponding quarter of the previous year. Total income (net of excise) stood at Rs 537.65 crore for the quarter against Rs 533.69 crore a year ago, the company told the Bombay Stock Exchange. Previous year figures are not comparable with the classification of this year as they include performance of power business and Bilts unit at Ashti, Maharashtra.

 HCL Infosystems has registered a consolidated net profit of Rs 84.9 crore for the quarter ended June 30. Consolidated profit before tax was Rs 123.6 crore in the quarter. Consolidated revenues stood at Rs 3,108.3 crore. The board has recommended a final dividend of 100 per cent per fully paid up share.

 The Bank of Shanghai has selected Teradata, a division of NCR Corporation, to build its enterprise data warehouse (EDW) after an evaluation process. The EDW will provide the bank with a single view of its business for analysis across departments and systems.

 Bausch amp; Lomb has launched an improved version of its PureVision contact lenses. The company claims that the lenses can be worn for 24 hours or more at a stretch. The lenses come at Rs 5,000 for a pack of 12 pairs.

 Usha Brita has made its foray into Bengal with a range of water purifiers Fontana, Atlantic, UV Power Saver and Water Guard Max. The company is a 50:50 joint venture between Usha Shriram and German firm Brita GmbH. 

 Ajanta Pharma has entered into an agreement to out-licence the technology of its anti-scar product Vaniza to Orient Europharma of Taiwan. Orient Europharma clocked sales worth $78.8 million in 2006 and is listed on the Taiwan OTC market.

 GlaxoSmithKline Pharmaceuticals Ltd has launched Carzec (carvedilol), a beta-blocker for patients suffering from heart failure and hypertension. 

 Royal Enfield Motors has inaugurated a brand store in Vishakhapatnam. The company also offers a ride scheme, under which a customer can ride a model for four to 24 hours before deciding to buy it. 

 The Pentax K10D camera has received awards including Best D-SLR Expert in Europe 2007 from TIPA, European Camera of the Year 2007-08 from EISA and Camera Grand Prix 2007 from the Camera Journal Press Club of Japan. The camera has a 10-megapixel CCD.

